40|$|In earlier research, we {{applied a}} linear {{weighted}} <b>cross-fading</b> function to ensure smooth concatenation. However, this can cause unnaturally shaped spectral trajectories. We propose context-sensitive <b>cross-fading.</b> To train this system, a perceptually validated cost function is needed, {{which is the}} focus of this paper. A corpus was designed to generate a variety of formant trajectory shapes. A perceptual experiment was performed and a multiple linear regression model was applied to predict perceptual quality ratings from various distances between <b>cross-faded</b> and natural trajectories. Results show that perceptual quality could be predicted well from the proposed distance measures. Index Terms: perceptual score, formant frequency, crossfading function, concatenation error...|$|R
